args:
As Curran and Cassandra take in a festival
together, they receive a report stating that the
imperial army is engaging in odd behavior,
which results in the cancellation of the special
nighttime lantern ceremony. Upon hearing this,
Cassandra quickly formulates a plan.
Hail there, shopkeep!\nOne hard candy, if you would.
You betcha, missy! The biggest one I got\nfor the prettiest little lady in town!
Thank you, dearieâ€”though you're likely\nto be disappointed when you find out\nmy actual age. ...Hmm? What's this?
Say there, shopkeep. What's with the\nbig group of people yonder?

Word is, that inquisitor there just bagged
himself a black marketeer selling dragon
horns and bones and such. Apparently he
was using a festival stall as a front.

Goodness, a proper crackdown! Still,
that's quite the ruckus coming from the
throng. Surely they've seen someone
tossed in the slammer before?

Ha ha! What you're hearin' is the voices of
the folks what had their stalls smashed up
in the raid. They've been arguin' with the
inquisitor for a spell now.
I already told you, I didn't mean any harm!\nThe smuggler ran through a gap in the\nstalls when I was trying to chase him!
I don't care WHAT you meant! You came\ncrashing in here like a boar in a crockery\nshop and wrecked all my merchandise!

Yeah, that's right! Maybe you unmasked
your troublemaker, but now I can't do
business no more! How're you gonna
make this right, huh?
Er, unfortunately, I don't exactly have\nany ready money on hand...
Cassandra! What brings you here,\nmy lady?
I heard all the hubbub and hullabaloo.\nDo you need money?
Oh, um... I mean, I couldn't... Yes.
*sigh* Sorry about making you cover my\ndebts. This is a real low moment for me.
Oh, I'm quite unbothered by it, dearie.\nYou can pay me back when we return\nto the Halidom.
That's kind, but I still feel like I need\nto thank you for this somehow.
In that case, perhaps you would be my\ngentleman caller and squire me about\nthe festival grounds, mmm?
Wait, really? That's all you want?
Oh, I've had my eyes on today's festival\nfor a while. Now take my arm and show\nan old lady a good time!
If that's what you want, my lady,\nI am happy to escort you.
...Or so I thought. I never imagined\nthat escorting a lady around a festival\nwould be this demanding!
Yoo hoo, Curran! I just bought these\nHinomotoan sweets called ï¼‚dango.ï¼‚
Er, but you already bought the hard candy,\nthe roasted corn, and the grilled chicken.\nAren't you maybe overdoing it?
Surely it's okay for a pair of folks like us\nto indulge a little on this night? Here,\nyou can have some of the dango.
(Hrk...so full... She's been taking one bite\nof everything and then handing it to me.)
Goodness, don't be modest now, dearie!\nA growing boy like you must be strong.
(Sort of impossible to refuse when one of\nyour elders wants to spoil you...)
Hello, Lathna. You look like you're having\nfun. Is there someone chaperoning you?
You, sir, claimed you were going out to do\ninquisitorial work, yet here you stand.
It would appear this ï¼‚workï¼‚ entailed\nstuffing your face with food from the stalls!
Ease up on the sarcasm, old friend;\nI've got my reasons. ...Say, now that\nI think of it, why don't you two join us?
Mostly I'm just being bossed around by\nCassandraâ€”which, mind you, IS work,\nbut not a hugely big deal.
If you'd prefer, you're more than welcome\nto repay the money I loaned you right now.
Well, not so much loaned as...covered me\nuntil I get back to the Halidom.
Besides, people get too tied up with the\nidea of money. It's there to be used,\nnot to use YOU.

That's all well and good, Curran, but it
wouldn't do to not repay your debts.
You're an adult, which means you
need to be responsible.
Oh, come on, you've got it all wrong.\nDon't judge me with those judgey eyes!
Heh heh. Our little Lathna is correct:\nYou should repay your debts properly,\nlike a grown up.
And with that, we are off.
Dammit, Heinwald... He knows full well\nwhat the deal is, but he's enjoying himself\nway too much to stop.
Well, I think that about covers everything,\ndearie. Still, it's a shame there were so\nmany closed-up stalls.
Yeah, I thought that was curious.\nMaybe there was some kind of problem?\n...Huh? Someone's coming over.
Luca and Ranzal? Where are the\ntwo of you going in such a hurry?
Got a bit'a trouble brewing, so we're\nroundin' up whatever allies are in\nthe area.
We got reports of an imperial army force\ngettin' up to no good somewhere near the\nnorthern border.

Goodness, how tactless to do something
like that on the day of a festival. However,
that doesn't mean they're planning to
attack this town necessarily, does it?
Yeah, I doubt they have much to gain\nfrom attacking a rural burg like this.
Still, them crossing the border willy-nilly\nain't a problem we can ignore, which is\nwhy we're gonna keep a close watch.
For now, yeahâ€”although looks like the\nnews already had an effect on business.
What effect are you referring to?

Highway's been cut off near the border,
which means no one can get throughâ€”
including the merchant what supplies
everybody else.
That's why ya got so many closed stallsâ€”\nfolks got nothin' to sell but air.
Well, that certainly does explain it.
Yeah, but the stalls aren't the biggest\nproblemâ€”they don't have any candles\nfor the lantern ceremony tonight.
That was the main event\nfor the evening, yes?
If memory serves, it involves lighting\nHinomoto-style lanterns floating them\noff down the river.
Ha! You sure know your stuff, Cassandra!\nBut without candles, the lanterns are\njust dark little paper floats.
And since that's really depressing,\nthey put the whole ceremony on hold.

Anyways, we're takin' up a defensive
position up on the northern highway.
If yer itchin' for a fight, yer welcome
to come join us.
'Course, I reckon it'll be tough to brawl\nwhile yer in those getups.
Maybe stickin' around town is better.\nYou can provide intel and junk, yeah?
I refuse to stand about like a bump on\na log when I might be of greater use.
I know a special task we can do.\nSomething tasty and important.
You also said ï¼‚we,ï¼‚ as in the two of us.\nWhat are you planning here, my lady?
